			<tr>
				<td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=57655&amp;sid=8563dcf24c5b960418d9fccfe88ba505#57655"><img src="templates/myth2/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Mon Dec 06, 2004 10:54 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re:                                                         </span></td>
				<td valign="top" align="right" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=57655&amp;sid=8563dcf24c5b960418d9fccfe88ba505"><img src="templates/myth2/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Mujahid wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In the end, though, that's just how the market works.  As long as you're talking about items that cannot be purchased from an NPC vendor, then the price of the spell components is going to drive the price of the spell.
<br />

<br />
If it costs me 1gp to make a spell, then my customer is just going to have to pay *at least* that price, plus whatever my standard mark-up is for certain items.
<br />

<br />
If the suppliers charge *too much* for their components...so much so that it is actually easier to just go harvest and make your own sub-combines...then the market will take care of itself.
<br />

<br />
The best way to have a free economy is to keep a "hands off" mentality, and just let "supply vs. demand" work its magic.
<br />

<br />
Now where the economy will get royally screwed is if they start placing some of these items on NPC vendors.  Because *those* vendors are not effected, at all, by "supply vs. demand".  They have an unlimited supply, and their price is fixed.  And going a week without business will not make the NPC vendor despawn <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
I sometimes check the market to see what other people are charging for spells.  When I find someone seriously undercutting (undercutting to the point of charging less than what it costs *me* to even *make* the spell), I just buy it off them and mark it up to what I usually charge.  They become my de facto supplier without even knowing it.  I have no idea where they got the spell, and I don't care.  If they're dumb enough to price an item beneath what it costs them to make it, then they are on the road to learning an invaluable lesson <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />  And if they were given the spell, or it was a drop, then we both gain.  Because they got "free money" when I bought it, and I'll turn a profit on it pretty quickly because I know what the going market rate is for the item, based upon what it costs to manufacture.
<br />

<br />
So, price gouging, while definitely a bad thing for the short term, takes care of itself in the long-term by changing the way people do business (or changing their approach to manufacturing) to avoid the price gouge.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The only caveat to all this is, there is/was a loophole in the code that allowed people to scribe (tier2 artisan class) essentials beyond level 9. In other words, there's a crapload of people who can make their own teir 2 stuff which gives them a royal advantage. This is perhaps why you see people undercutting so heavily. I hope SOE comes along with some nastyass "fix" that sets them all back to level 1 artisan.
<br />

<br />
edit&gt; oh and of course it would clear ALL their scribed books,  (muhahaha..) not just the ones they shouldn't have. (muahhahha!!) Hey I can dream. It's not like it would even horribly hurt them to have to buy the dropped books again since they've made a mint illegally already. I saw one guy was selling 14 copies of scholar essentials 11 for 2gp each.  Did some corrupt seller have the craftsman books on sale though? Nooo  of course not. Bastards. Apparently all the bad eggs (also read as, smart people) are scholars.</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Scarecrowe on Mon Dec 06, 2004 2:20 pm; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
